The Soviet Union suffered millions of deaths fighting Germany in World War II, and has  said the idea of German reunification is "dangerous and unrealistic".
There has been  speculation that the Kremlin might stipulate German neutrality as a price for  reunification, meaning a NATO without Germany.
Chancellor Kohl assured visiting  United States senators that West Germany will not forsake NATO under any  circumstance.
Presidents Bush and Gorbachev are to begin a shipboard summit off Malta on Saturday.
The dramatic events in East Germany and the whirlwind reforms in other East bloc  countries are likely to be a major topic of discussion. 
